Clearly not. The creature merely hissed and tried to charge straight at Thassalin. Fortunately, despite its size, it was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi couldn't help but scream when she almost lost her grip on its too smooth scales.
"HOW DO YOU KILL THEM?," shouted Nyssi.
"AIM FOR THEIR HEAD!."
"THAT'S NOT GOING TO BE EASY!."
Thassalin exhaled, then circled around to get closer to the mountain he called his home. The black beast followed, somewhat panicked when a flash of fire struck it from behind. The creature hadn't noticed that it was no longer alone. Its panic grew when Thassalin slowed down, then violently hit it in the head with his tail, causing it to veer off its course.
Growling and hissing, the creature gained altitude and spat into the air. Suddenly, everything turned black, as if the monster was sucking in the light of the sky and replacing it with a perpetual cloud of night.
With no visibility left, Thassalin tried to retreat, but scraped the treetops before crashing into the clearing. As if she had known exactly where he had fallen, the creature charged straight at him, dragging the dark cloud in its wake.
"Kayel!", exclaimed Tenuk as he emerged from the cloud and began flying in circles trying to spot Nyssi and Thassalin below, in the darkness. "What do we do, Kayel? Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Down below, Nyssi got up as best she could. She was sure she had broken something, but her strange, unnatural healing powers had already started taking effect. The same could not be said of Thassalin, who was lying on a mound, leaning against the only tree that had not bent under his weight. Nyssi did her best to try and reach Thassalin, but she could not see more than two meters ahead of her. Everything was plunged into darkness, swallowed by the impious shadows. And within those shadows, something was screaming.
An awful, club-like tail came swinging down beside Nyssi, knocking her off her feet. She noted, however, that the tail was swishing around, not aiming at her. The creature, from the little that Nyssi could see and hear, was growling and clawing at the shadows it had created. Something was teleporting through the darkness, striking the monster, disorienting it.
A gunshot rang out suddenly, and the monster collapsed silently, motionless. The darkness surrounding them dissipated, revealing what had happened. Standing on the creature was Kayel, holding a rifle and breathing heavily.
"This... is the strangest shadow leap I've ever done... Thanto kat'olon...", gasped Kayel. His eyes shone with a dark glow, and a dark energy coursed through his body. However, as he spoke, Kayel's organic plating regained its color, and his eyes returned to their normal yellow hue.
It took a moment for Nyssi to understand what had happened. They all knew that Kayel possessed strange shadow powers. He rarely used them, as most people considered them impious and rather terrifying. But Nyssi didn't know that Kayel could use these powers in the dark. And, judging by his behavior, Kayel seemed quite surprised himself.
"Are you okay ?", couldn't help but ask Nyssi.
"Yes, I'm okay. I killed something. It'll be better in a minute." Kayel examined his work, as Tenuk made his way to land beside him, returning to his normal Spast form.
Now that the creature was no longer moving, they could see better what it was. Its skin was black as coal and slimy, but the saliva continued to stick to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long claws, and two straight horns came out of its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what this thing was, something howled and rushed out from a nearby bush. However, the beast didn't have time to reach them, because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, throwing it at Nyssi's feet. Taking no chances, she grabbed her rifle and immediately shot it in the head, killing the creature instantly.
"Oops...", muttered Retvik from the driver's seat, before clumsily cutting the engine and jumping out of the truck. "I, uh, didn't mean to do that. Are you all right?"
"You practically missed all the action," regretted Tenuk. "Where were you?"
"You all left me behind. I came here as fast as I could," sighed Retvik. "May I know what these vile things are?"
Retvik's question fortunately received an answer from Thassalin, who had just risen. He was all cut up and scratched everywhere and seemed a bit disoriented, but he didn't look too badly hurt.
"YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTED! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. CREATURES LEFT HERE WHEN THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"You mean... the horrible monster god that we... helped to kill?", stammered Tenuk.
"YES. EXACTLY. THERE MAY BE OTHERS, BUT I DIDN'T MANAGE TO AIM FOR THEIR HEADS. I'M SHORT A RIFLE. PLUS, TWO AGAINST ONE, THAT'S NOT FAIR, IS IT?" Thassalin walked over to Kayel and patted his head. "THANK YOU, KID. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. JUST LESS MURDEROUS AND LESS CAPABLE OF KILLING UNIVERSES."
"Uh... thanks... I guess", said Kayel with a shrug. "So, are we done here?"
Nissy shrugged her shoulders, then grabbed her camera to photograph the beasts, now thoroughly dead. She then took out her favorite dagger, that of the god of death, and began cutting one of the creature's horns, before moving on to the other. But as she finished, the creatures caught fire and quickly turned into piles of ashes. The same thing happened to the horns that Nyssi had cut.
"Well... it's both convenient and not convenient at all," she sighed. "At least I still have the photos..."
